data.text: Not really a fast food kind of girl but dang!! Everyone should at least try Febo at least once. Walking along the streets of Amsterdam, I have seen at least one Febo at every corner I turn. This Dutch fast food chain is seemingly popular and it works like a vending machine where you insert in coins and get the stuff u want. This is so good! It's a spicy croquette stuffed with beef and peanuts.

data.text: De Pijp, an Amsterdam neighborhood found just south of the canal ring, translates into English as 'The Pipeâ€™ - an early reference to either the public prostitution or the shape of the neighborhood. Historians disagree.  For the last couple of years, an actual pipe, the Amsterdam metro, has been digging its way under De Pijp. Not surprisingly, building a subway in a city that's below sea level is kind of tricky and led to the misfortune which was the 'Great Heineken Debacle of 2014,' when the Heineken brewery fell into a giant sinkhole. Even without its top tourist destination and the constant fear of sudden, gaping pits, De Pijp has managed to evolve into a neighborhood that lifestyle bloggers describe as â€œtrendyâ€ and â€œalive.â€ On sunny afternoons, try Sarphatipark if you're inclined to pop the top and get some color. The Albert Cuyp Market (#albertcuypmarkt) is (supposedly) the â€œlargest daytime market in Europeâ€ and has a few interesting food stands, but you're better off heading to Pho 91 (@pho91amsterdam), Spaghetteria (@spaghetteria_pastabar), or The Butcher (@thebutcheramsterdam). (**TIP - Thereâ€™s also great Surinamese just off the market on Eerste van der Helststraat.) For shopping, thereâ€™s Charlie + Mary (@charlieplusmary), All The Luck In The Worldâ€¦ (@alltheluckintheworld), and several other boutiques on the same block of Gerard Doustraat. If you're working away from the office, Stadskantine has plenty of window seating and a good atmosphere. For coffee, Scandinavian Embassy (@scandinavianembassy) and CT Coffee & Coconuts (@coffeecoconuts) are good spots. De Pijp, an Amsterdam neighborhood found just south of the canal ring, translates into English as 'The Pipeâ€™ - an early reference to either the public prostitution or the shape of the neighborhood. Historians disagree.  For the last couple of years, an actual pipe, the Amsterdam metro, has been digging its way under De Pijp. Not surprisingly, building a subway in a city that's below sea level is kind of tricky and led to the misfortune which was the 'Great Heineken Debacle of 2014,' when the Heineken brewery fell into a giant sinkhole. Even without its top tourist destination and the constant fear of sudden, gaping pits, De Pijp has managed to evolve into a neighborhood that lifestyle bloggers describe as â€œtrendyâ€ and â€œalive.â€ On sunny afternoons, try Sarphatipark if you're inclined to pop the top and get some color. The Albert Cuyp Market (#albertcuypmarkt) is (supposedly) the â€œlargest daytime market in Europeâ€ and has a few interesting food stands, but you're better off heading to Pho 91 (@pho91amsterdam), Spaghetteria (@spaghetteria_pastabar), or The Butcher (@thebutcheramsterdam). (**TIP - Thereâ€™s also great Surinamese just off the market on Eerste van der Helststraat.) For shopping, thereâ€™s Charlie + Mary (@charlieplusmary), All The Luck In The Worldâ€¦ (@alltheluckintheworld), and several other boutiques on the same block of Gerard Doustraat. If you're working away from the office, Stadskantine has plenty of window seating and a good atmosphere. For coffee, Scandinavian Embassy (@scandinavianembassy) and CT Coffee & Coconuts (@coffeecoconuts) are good spots. data.text: We have a Fish and Chips revival in Amsterdam. ViscafÃ© De Gouden Hoek, close to the Westerpark, was the first offering mainly Fish and Chips from daily catches. We love the ambiance which is very stylish and strengthening the concept. Here is what they do menu wise: some classic startes like croquettes, oysters and crab, but the main focus is of course on fish and chips. You choose one of the daily catches and combine it with one of three crusts with accompanying sauce. Choose from the classic crust with remoulade, a panko-crust with piccalilli or tempura-crust with Japanese Sriracha. When you donâ€™t have enough at hand, daily catches ask for good communication between kitchen and service staff. Which in our case didn't go very well. We were surprised when two out of three dishes served had a totally different fish then the one we had ordered. And we had to find out ourselves. Ah what the heck, the taste was good. Service wasnâ€™t to stable though. Some get it, others donâ€™t. Do we recommend this place? Yup!
